Sinéad Quinn (Irish: Sinéad Ní Chuinn; born 24 March 1980) is a Northern Irish singer, best known as a contestant in the first series of the UK BBC TV series Fame Academy in 2002.
She later went on to sign a recording contract, released an album, and had a #2 UK single with "I Can't Break Down" in February 2003.
Her debut single, "I Can’t Break Down", was released 10 February 2003.
The single sold around 70,000 copies, finishing in 65th place for the top selling UK singles of 2003.
With the backing of a guitar based group she went on a University tour in 2003.

She has played to a full-house at Music Live 2003 at the National Exhibition Centre and, in 2005, she supported Children in Need with a performance and sang at the switch-on of Christmas lights in Coventry.

Late in 2005 Quinn was invited by the Irish President Mary McAleese "to a reception to celebrate [her] contribution to the entertainment industry in Ireland" at the President's official residence, Áras an Uachtaráin.
Quinn played the role of Beth in the 2007 live tour of Jeff Wayne's Musical Version of The War of the Worlds.

Within a week of leaving the Fame Academy, Quinn signed a £1 million, five-album record deal with Mercury Records.
In the years since leaving Fame Academy, she has had a regular list of public performances.
The same year she performed at and judged the regional finals for Girl Guiding UK's talent competition Guiding Star.
